Description: Convert pointer_motion_absolute coordinates to wl_fixed_t.
 .
 The generated Qt wayland binding for the ``fake-input`` protocol
 declares ``pointer_motion_absolute(wl_fixed_t x, wl_fixed_t y)``.
 ``wl_fixed_t`` is the 24.8 signed fixed-point integer format used on
 the wire by every libwayland client/server, and the canonical way to
 produce one from a floating-point logical coordinate is the libwayland
 helper ``wl_fixed_from_double()``.
 .
 ``PlasmaScreencastV1Session::sendEvent`` passes the raw double-typed
 coordinates from ``QPointF::x()`` / ``QPointF::y()`` directly into
 that call:
 .
     d->remoteInterface->pointer_motion_absolute(
         logicalPosition.x(), logicalPosition.y());
 .
 Because the function signature takes ``wl_fixed_t`` (a typedef for
 ``int32_t``), C++ performs an implicit ``double → int32_t``
 *truncating* conversion rather than a fixed-point multiplication.
 The logical value ``512.0`` is sent as the integer ``512`` on the
 wire, which a wayland peer decodes as a ``wl_fixed_t`` whose
 floating-point interpretation is ``512 / 256 = 2.0``. In other
 words, every pointer coordinate is transmitted at 1/256 of its
 intended magnitude -- a 1024x768 virtual monitor ends up reporting
 pointer positions in the 0..4 px range at the top-left corner.
 .
 The cursor on the KWin side follows those tiny values, so it
 appears pinned near (0,0). Two user-visible consequences result:
 .
   * Moving the mouse on mstsc makes the remote cursor "disappear"
     into the upper-left -- exactly where Plasma's default Overview
     hot-corner lives -- so Overview (the "Present Windows" effect)
     triggers almost continuously. That's the spectacular symptom
     a tester sees first.
   * Clicks and keypresses meant for whatever surface is under the
     mstsc cursor actually target whichever surface is at (0,0) --
     typically nothing, or a screen edge -- so they are silently
     dropped. Overview's own search field, which is a KWin-internal
     effect surface rather than a regular wl_surface, is one of the
     few places keyboard input still does something, because KWin
     dispatches keys into the effect directly without routing through
     the unicode-owning surface. That is why users report "typing
     works in the window switcher's search box but not in regular
     applications".
 .
 The sibling ``axis()`` call two lines down already uses
 ``wl_fixed_from_double()`` correctly:
 .
     d->remoteInterface->axis(
         WL_POINTER_AXIS_VERTICAL_SCROLL,
         wl_fixed_from_double(delta.y()));
 .
 so this patch applies the same conversion to the
 ``pointer_motion_absolute`` arguments for consistency and correct
 wire-format semantics.
 .
 ``keyboard_key()`` is unaffected: it takes ``uint32_t`` scancode /
 state, which are plain integers, not fixed-point.
 ``PortalSession::sendEvent`` uses ``NotifyPointerMotionAbsolute``
 over DBus, which accepts IEEE-754 doubles directly, so the same
 arithmetic is already correct for the portal code path.
